1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,129
You're listening to: When Our Kafka Consumer Lag Hit 2 Million: A Debugging War Story.

2
00:00:06,129 --> 00:00:11,382
Our order events fell 2 million messages behind and nobody noticed for hours.

3
00:00:11,382 --> 00:00:20,961
A practical walkthrough of diagnosing Kafka consumer lag — partitions, rebalances, poison messages — and the fixes that got us back to real time.

4
00:00:20,961 --> 00:00:22,007
Let's get started.

5
00:00:22,007 --> 00:00:26,514
The support ticket said: "Customers are seeing yesterday's order status."

6
00:00:26,514 --> 00:00:30,180
That is a strange sentence when your system is "real-time."

7
00:00:30,180 --> 00:00:38,425
It meant our event pipeline — the thing that propagates an order through payment, inventory, and notification — was running hours in the past.

8
00:00:38,425 --> 00:00:46,983
When I opened the Kafka dashboard, the consumer lag on our orders topic read 2,147,000 messages and climbing.

9
00:00:46,983 --> 00:00:49,639
Here is how I found the cause and dug us out.

10
00:00:49,639 --> 00:00:56,850
If you are new to Kafka, my event streaming deep-dive and event-driven architecture guide cover the concepts I lean on here.

11
00:00:56,850 --> 00:01:00,973
Now, let's talk about First: what consumer lag actually means.

12
00:01:00,973 --> 00:01:03,954
Lag is simple but worth stating precisely.

13
00:01:03,954 --> 00:01:07,415
For each partition, Kafka tracks two offsets:

14
00:01:07,415 --> 00:01:11,466
Log-end offset — the offset of the latest message produced..

15
00:01:11,466 --> 00:01:15,048
Committed offset — the offset your consumer group has processed..

16
00:01:15,048 --> 00:01:18,774
Lag = log-end offset − committed offset.

17
00:01:18,774 --> 00:01:23,389
Two million lag means two million messages were produced that we had not yet handled.

18
00:01:23,389 --> 00:01:32,403
The danger of lag is that it is silent: nothing errors, producers keep producing happily, and consumers keep consuming — just too slowly.

19
00:01:32,403 --> 00:01:40,697
The only symptom is staleness, which users feel long before any alert fires (unless you alert on lag directly, which we now do).

20
00:01:40,697 --> 00:01:44,146
That third line told the story before I read anything else.

21
00:01:44,146 --> 00:01:48,281
Moving on to Symptom 1: one partition stuck at offset 0.

22
00:01:48,281 --> 00:01:55,913
Partition 2's CURRENT-OFFSET was 0 — it had never committed a single message — while the others were making progress.

23
00:01:55,913 --> 00:02:03,942
In Kafka, a partition is consumed by exactly one consumer in the group, and ordering is guaranteed only within a partition.

24
00:02:03,942 --> 00:02:07,103
If one partition is stuck, one consumer is stuck.

25
00:02:07,103 --> 00:02:09,242
The cause: a poison message.

26
00:02:09,242 --> 00:02:15,048
Some upstream service had published an order event with a malformed JSON body to partition 2.

27
00:02:15,048 --> 00:02:24,134
Our consumer deserialized in a tight loop, threw on that message, did not commit, retried from the same offset, threw again — forever.

28
00:02:24,134 --> 00:02:29,435
It was wedged on a single bad record while a quarter of all traffic piled up behind it.

29
00:02:29,435 --> 00:02:33,052
The lesson: never let one bad message block a partition.

30
00:02:33,052 --> 00:02:35,216
The fix is a dead-letter topic.

31
00:02:35,216 --> 00:02:42,199
Now a malformed message is parked in orders.dlq for later inspection and the partition keeps flowing.

32
00:02:42,199 --> 00:02:48,064
The moment I deployed this, partition 2 started moving and a third of the lag drained within minutes.

33
00:02:48,064 --> 00:02:51,935
Next up: Symptom 2: constant rebalancing.

34
00:02:51,935 --> 00:02:56,298
The other three partitions were making progress but far too slowly.

35
00:02:56,298 --> 00:03:02,728
The broker logs were full of rebalance events — the consumer group was rebalancing every minute or so.

36
00:03:02,728 --> 00:03:08,665
During a rebalance, all consumers in the group stop processing while partitions are reassigned.

37
00:03:08,665 --> 00:03:13,425
Rebalance every minute, and you spend a big chunk of every minute frozen.

38
00:03:13,425 --> 00:03:17,848
The trigger was max.poll.interval.ms.

39
00:03:17,848 --> 00:03:27,764
Our per-message processing had gotten slower (an added synchronous call to a downstream service), so occasionally a single poll() batch took longer than the configured interval.

40
00:03:27,764 --> 00:03:32,067
Kafka assumed the consumer was dead, kicked it out, and rebalanced.

41
00:03:32,067 --> 00:03:36,478
The evicted consumer rejoined, triggering another rebalance.

42
00:03:36,478 --> 00:03:38,197
A self-perpetuating churn.

43
00:03:38,197 --> 00:03:40,781
Process less per poll, or faster.

44
00:03:40,781 --> 00:03:47,271
I reduced max.poll.records so each batch was guaranteed to finish well within the interval..

45
00:03:47,271 --> 00:03:52,475
Make the slow downstream call asynchronous instead of blocking the poll loop on it..

46
00:03:52,475 --> 00:04:01,887
Disabling auto-commit matters too: auto-commit can advance the offset before you have actually processed a message, so a crash silently drops data.

47
00:04:01,887 --> 00:04:04,723
Commit explicitly, after the work is done.

48
00:04:04,723 --> 00:04:09,038
Let's explore Symptom 3: not enough parallelism.

49
00:04:09,050 --> 00:04:16,680
With poison messages dead-lettered and rebalances calmed, we were keeping up with new traffic but the 2M backlog was draining slowly.

50
00:04:16,680 --> 00:04:22,978
The constraint is structural: the maximum parallelism of a consumer group equals the number of partitions.

51
00:04:22,978 --> 00:04:30,706
Our orders topic had 4 partitions, so at most 4 consumers could work in parallel, no matter how many pods we ran.

52
00:04:30,706 --> 00:04:45,033
For the drain, I temporarily scaled the consumer pods to 4 (one per partition) so every partition had a dedicated worker, and increased the topic's partition count for headroom going forward (new partitions only help new keys, but it raised the ceiling).

53
00:04:45,033 --> 00:04:52,209
The backlog of 2M drained in about 40 minutes once all four partitions had a healthy, dedicated consumer.

54
00:04:52,209 --> 00:04:54,420
Now let's look at What I changed permanently.

55
00:04:54,420 --> 00:04:56,740
Alert on lag, not just errors.

56
00:04:56,740 --> 00:05:02,064
We now page when lag on any partition exceeds a threshold for more than a few minutes.

57
00:05:02,064 --> 00:05:04,757
Staleness is now a first-class alert..

58
00:05:04,757 --> 00:05:07,533
Dead-letter topic for every consumer.

59
00:05:07,533 --> 00:05:11,151
A single malformed message can never again wedge a partition..

60
00:05:11,151 --> 00:05:13,795
Explicit commits, smaller poll batches.

61
00:05:13,795 --> 00:05:18,254
Predictable processing time prevents the rebalance death-spiral..

62
00:05:18,254 --> 00:05:25,658
Partition count sized for peak parallelism, with consumers autoscaled toward (but not above) the partition count..

63
00:05:25,658 --> 00:05:28,038
Now, let's talk about The mental model.

64
00:05:28,038 --> 00:05:33,495
If you remember one thing: Kafka lag is a queueing problem, and the queue is per-partition.

65
00:05:33,495 --> 00:05:45,826
Almost every lag incident reduces to one of three things — a partition is blocked (poison message), the consumers are frozen (rebalancing), or you are out of parallelism (too few partitions).

66
00:05:45,826 --> 00:05:52,052
Check those three, in that order, and you will diagnose most lag incidents in minutes instead of hours.

